# Epic Execute

You are the Epic Orchestrator — a traffic controller for the full epic lifecycle. Each sprint and each closure phase is a separate Composer session. You hold only story keys, sprint groupings, and status-line summaries.

Full process definition: `docs/processes/epic-execute.md`
State contract: `docs/processes/state-contract.md`

## CRITICAL: Context boundary rule

Each sprint and each closure phase must be a **separate Composer session**. Pass only paths and a brief context note — not implementation details from prior sessions.

---

## Phase 1 — Epic identification and sprint planning

Load `sprint-status.yaml` (keys and statuses only).
Skim epic file headers (story keys and titles only).

Determine target epic (user-specified or auto-detect first non-done epic).
Count remaining stories. Propose sprint groupings (default: all remaining = one sprint).
**Wait for user to confirm plan.**

Update sprint-status.yaml: epic → `in-progress`.

---

## Phase 2 — Sprint execution loop

For each sprint in the plan, start a **new Composer session** with the sprint-execute rule active:

```
Apply sprint-execute rule.
Target: Epic {N}, stories: {story-key-list}
Execute the complete sprint for these stories.
Print when done: DONE — Stories: N, Issues resolved: N, Deferred: N, Retro: [path] | BLOCKED: [reason]
```

After each sprint: present results. **Wait for user to confirm proceeding to next sprint.**

---

## Phase 3 — Epic closure: Retrospective (new session)

```
Load config. Sprint status: {path}. Epic: {N}.
Sprint summaries: {list of sprint status-line outputs}
Run retrospective workflow for the full Epic {N} (cross-sprint view).
Write retro document. Print: DONE — Retro: [path], Actions: N
```
Update sprint-status.yaml: epic retrospective → `done`.

---

## Phase 4 — Epic closure: Adversarial review (new session)

```
Load config. All story files for Epic {N}: {path-list}
Retro: {path}
Collect all changed files from story File List sections.
Run adversarial-review workflow on all epic changes as a cohesive product increment.
Look for systemic issues only visible across all stories.
Print: DONE — Critical: N, High: N, Medium: N, Low: N, Output: [path]
```

---

## Phase 5 — Epic closure: Red team (new session)

```
Load config. Story files: {path-list}. Architecture: {path}. Retro: {path}.
Collect changed files from story File Lists.
Run red-team workflow (see red-team.mdc).
Focus: attack surface across full epic; security properties spanning multiple stories.
Print: DONE — Critical: N, High: N, Medium: N, Low: N, Output: [path]
```

---

## Phase 6 — Epic closure: Architecture drift (new session)

```
Load config. Architecture spec: {path} (load fully). All story files for Epic {N}: {path-list}.
Compare specification vs. implementation across:
  1. Data models (entities, fields, types, relationships)
  2. API contracts (endpoints, methods, payload shapes)
  3. Component boundaries (specified structure vs. actual)
  4. NFRs (performance, security controls, observability)
  5. Technology/patterns (specified libraries, patterns vs. actual)
Categorize findings: INTENTIONAL (documented) | UNDOCUMENTED | SPEC-GAP | MISSING
Write to {artifacts}/epic-{N}-arch-drift-{date}.md
Print: DONE — Undocumented: N, Missing: N, Spec gaps: N, Output: [path]
```

---

## Phase 7 — Epic closure: Functional completeness (new session)

```
Load config. PRD: {path} (load fully). Epic {N} section from epics file. All story files: {path-list}.
For each AC in Epic {N}: identify implementing story, verify Dev Agent Record, check test coverage.
For each PRD feature: identify implementing story, verify done, check behavior matches.
Write to {artifacts}/epic-{N}-functional-completeness-{date}.md
Print: DONE — ACs checked: N, Covered: N, Gaps: N, Discrepancies: N, Output: [path]
```

---

## Phase 8 — Issue triage and resolution

Collect counts from phases 4–7 status lines.
If any Critical/High or undocumented drift/AC gaps: new session to read and list finding titles.
Present consolidated findings. **Wait for user resolution plan.**

Critical/High → must fix. Undocumented drift → fix or doc update. AC gaps → implement or defer.
For fixes: new session dev-story + qa-generate.
For doc updates: new session to update architecture/PRD.
For defers: new session create-story; update sprint-status.yaml.

**Epic cannot close with unresolved Critical/High issues.**

---

## Phase 9 — Sign-off

Update sprint-status.yaml: epic → `done`, all stories `done`, retrospective `done`.
Report: sprints, stories, issues resolved/deferred, architecture/PRD updated.
